📌 Java: Why void methods cannot be printed
🔎 Problem Example
class square {
    int side;
    Scanner in = new Scanner(System.in);

    public void getValues() {   // 👈 void method
        System.out.println("Enter side of Square");
        side = in.nextInt();
    }

    public int area() {
        return side * side;
    }
}

public class Q3 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        square cla = new square();
        System.out.println(cla.getValues());   // ❌ ERROR
        System.out.println(cla.area());        // ✅ works
    }
}

⚠️ Why error occurs?

void = method does not return anything.

But System.out.println(cla.getValues()); tries to print a return value.

Since nothing is returned → compiler error.

✅ Correct Usage
public class Q3 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        square cla = new square();
        cla.getValues();                     // ✅ just call void method
        System.out.println(cla.area());      // ✅ prints result
    }
}

📖 Notes

Void methods

Perform an action (input, update, print, etc.).

Do not return any value.

Call them simply:

obj.methodName();


Non-void methods

Return a value (e.g., int, String, double).

Can be printed or stored:

System.out.println(obj.methodName());
int result = obj.methodName();


✅ Key Rule to Remember:
👉 void = “do something”
👉 non-void = “give me something”